title: Days Before Germans Vote, Merkel Is Where She Didn’t Want to Be: On the Stump
content: The race for chancellor is tightening, but Angela Merkel says Armin Laschet is the man to fill her shoes.

title: Photos of an Eruption: Canary Island Volcano Sends Thousands Fleeing
content: This is what it looks like in La Palma, where the most powerful volcanic eruption in half a century has upended life for islanders.

title: Has Covid Cost Australia Its Love for Freedom?
content: Half the country is locked down, and its borders remain closed. But most Australians are willing to make these sacrifices in pursuit of a collective freedom from fear of the virus.

title: In Sicily Slums, a 113-Year Wait for Housing May Be Over
content: After a 1908 earthquake in Messina, the displaced were moved into temporary shacks. Thousands still live in squalor, but the pandemic has pushed Rome to take action at last.

title: France, Striving for Global Power, Still Struggles to Get It
content: Though often seen as vanity or pique, France’s assertiveness abroad is calibrated to manage a quandary it has faced since World War II: how to act as an independent power while depending on allies.

title: Australia Court Orders Ex-Principal to Be Tried on Abuse Charges
content: Malka Leifer, who was extradited from Israel after a long battle, pleaded not guilty to 70 counts.

title: Top Adviser to Ukrainian President Is Targeted in an Assassination Attempt
content: President Volodymyr Zelensky said he was returning to Ukraine from New York immediately after giving his U.N. speech. The adviser, Serhiy Shefir, was unharmed, but his driver was shot and wounded in the attack.

title: New Zealand wants vaccination rates near 90 percent.
India Opens Its Highest Military Ranks to Women After Lengthy Fight
content: Combat roles will still be restricted, but female soldiers and sailors will have greater access to the academy that leads to choice leadership positions.

title: Congressional Brinkmanship
content: Is the U.S. government headed for another showdown over the debt ceiling?

title: Your Thursday Briefing
content: Biden’s call for global vaccine cooperation.

title: At Covid Summit, Biden Sets Ambitious Goals for Vaccinating the World
content: But his plans face a tough road as pressure grows for big pharmaceutical companies to share their vaccine technologies with poorer nations.

title: F.D.A. Authorizes Pfizer Booster Shots for Older and At-Risk Americans
content: Regulators said that people over 65 or at high risk of severe Covid-19 were eligible for an extra shot, setting up a staggered national booster campaign.

title: The U.S. Is Lifting Travel Restrictions for Visitors. What Do the New Rules Mean?
content: The Biden administration will allow vaccinated international travelers to enter the United States, including those from previously banned countries. Details remain to be worked out, but here is what we know so far.

title: Biden Pushes Deterrent Border Policy After Promising ‘Humane’ Approach
content: The deportation of Haitian migrants is a stark example of how President Biden has deployed some of the most aggressive approaches to immigration put in place by former President Donald J. Trump.

title: Biden Declared the War Over. But Wars Go On.
content: The president’s assertion after the withdrawal from Afghanistan that the United States is not at war for the first time in 20 years ignored continued smaller-scale conflicts.

title: Your Thursday Briefing
content: Biden urges a ‘go big’ response to the pandemic.

title: Arctic Sea Ice Hits Annual Low, but It’s Not as Low as Recent Years
content: Cool conditions north of Alaska in August reduced melting, scientists say, but the overall is still downward.

title: Mormons should wear face masks ‘at all times’ in temples, the church instructs.
content: “We want to do everything possible to allow temples to remain open,” the church’s president, Russell M. Nelson, and his two top counselors wrote in a letter released Wednesday.

title: Some experts say that Biden’s new plan for donating vaccines falls short.
content: Of the 1.1 billion doses that the United States has committed to donations, only 300 million are expected to be shipped this year.

title: Nearly 1 in 4 hospitals treating Covid in Afghanistan have shut down, the W.H.O. warns.
content: After the Taliban took over, Western donor nations withdrew from a program that financed clinics across the country through the Afghan health ministry, the W.H.O. said.

title: Germany is ending salary subsidies for unvaccinated workers who are quarantined.

content: The two leaders spoke by telephone for the first time since President Emmanuel Macron of France recalled his ambassador to the United States over a new defense agreement.

title: Biden announces a new science advisory panel for pandemics, climate change and other issues.

content: Argentina’s vice president, Cristina Fernández de Kirchner, masterminded the plan to elect President Alberto Fernández. Now they’re openly sparring.

title: China Says It Won’t Build New Coal Plants Abroad. What Does That Mean?
content: Beijing is the undisputed king of coal, but the announcement at the United Nations General Assembly this week was cautiously welcomed by climate experts.

title: Australia could open its borders by Christmas, its tourism minister says.

title: Brazil’s health minister tests positive for the coronavirus at the U.N. General Assembly.
content: The minister was accompanying President Jair Bolsonaro, who has refused to be vaccinated.

title: They Never Could Work From Home. These Are Their Stories.
content: A parallel universe of millions of employees did not have the luxury of thinking about returning to the office — they never left. Six workers share their experiences.

title: Pressure Grows on U.S. Companies to Share Covid Vaccine Technology
content: Moderna accepted $2.5 billion in taxpayer money to develop its Covid-19 vaccine. But officials in the U.S. and overseas are having trouble persuading the company to license its technology.
